WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:08.570
BRUCE: On behalf of the Reading
Odyssey and Collaborative

00:00:08.570 --> 00:00:12.620
Gain and Google, to this
special presentation

00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:15.260
of "Julius Caesar," one of the
greatest works of all time.

00:00:17.840 --> 00:00:21.436
It's kind of fitting that we're
presenting this book at Google

00:00:21.436 --> 00:00:23.060
within the entire
tech community, which

00:00:23.060 --> 00:00:26.530
puts such a big emphasis
on product experience

00:00:26.530 --> 00:00:29.120
and user experience and design.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:31.310
These books-- I
met Bob Strassler,

00:00:31.310 --> 00:00:33.080
the series editor,
10 years ago when

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:35.000
I was a reporter at "Forbes."

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.770
Now I'm in PR, if
you will, because it

00:00:39.770 --> 00:00:41.990
was an amazing story of an
entrepreneur, if you will,

00:00:41.990 --> 00:00:45.650
or someone who had retired
and saw a need in the market

00:00:45.650 --> 00:00:50.240
for essentially, a
usable classics series.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:53.800
Because the books that everyone
was using for almost 100 years,

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:55.317
those Penguin
editions are dense.

00:00:55.317 --> 00:00:56.900
There's maybe one
map in the beginning

00:00:56.900 --> 00:00:58.520
with dozens of labels on it.

00:00:58.520 --> 00:00:59.180
No footnotes.

00:00:59.180 --> 00:00:59.882
No context.

00:00:59.882 --> 00:01:02.340
And you're just thrown into it
as a student in high school.

00:01:02.340 --> 00:01:04.636
And obviously, it turns
off a lot of people,

00:01:04.636 --> 00:01:06.260
and they never get
back to the classics

00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:08.300
again, which is a huge loss.

00:01:08.300 --> 00:01:09.400
So Bob said, wait.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:11.020
I can fix that.

00:01:11.020 --> 00:01:13.790
So he took his own
money and decided

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:16.250
to design an edition
that had all of that.

00:01:16.250 --> 00:01:18.590
Every page would be
dripping with context.

00:01:18.590 --> 00:01:22.010
There'd be a place, a time,
footnotes, side notes,

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:23.960
pictures, maps in context.

00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:28.790
He did it all by hand, hired a
few people out of the academia

00:01:28.790 --> 00:01:30.260
after getting a
lot of rejections

00:01:30.260 --> 00:01:33.110
from university professors
saying, you can't do this.

00:01:33.110 --> 00:01:34.070
You're an amateur.

00:01:34.070 --> 00:01:35.528
Well, that's usually
the best kinds

00:01:35.528 --> 00:01:37.010
of people, the
passionate amateur.

00:01:37.010 --> 00:01:38.810
So this series came out.

00:01:38.810 --> 00:01:41.030
The first edition came
out almost 20 years ago,

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:42.584
"Landmark Thucydides."

00:01:42.584 --> 00:01:44.000
I caught up with
Bob 10 years ago,

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.190
and he was just putting
out a second one, "Landmark

00:01:46.190 --> 00:01:46.750
Herodotus."

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:49.430
And since then, there's
been at least two more.

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:50.900
This is the fifth, I think.

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:54.890
And it's one of the bestselling
classics series of all time.

00:01:54.890 --> 00:01:57.387
So without further ado, I
won't give any much more away,

00:01:57.387 --> 00:01:59.720
because Bob will tell you the
story of how it all began.

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:02.090
And we'll hear a
lot from the editor

00:02:02.090 --> 00:02:04.610
of this particular volume,
Kurt, who's here as well.

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:08.060
A professor from Brown, who's
one of the world's experts

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:10.988
on Caesar, to tell you
the story behind the book.

00:02:10.988 --> 00:02:14.740
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:16.380
ROBERT STRASSLER:
Thank you, Bruce.

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:19.830
It's a pleasure
to be here today.

00:02:19.830 --> 00:02:23.700
I am proposing to spend
a little further time

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:25.890
on what Landmark books are.

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:29.610
And to explain why and
how they were determined

00:02:29.610 --> 00:02:31.140
to be the way they are.

00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:34.060
And how we hope to accomplish
certain things with them.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:38.070
And then after that, we'll
talk about the challenges

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:40.650
to Landmark books
that were posed

00:02:40.650 --> 00:02:43.560
by the immense amount
of data that is known

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:45.924
about Caesar and his world.

00:02:45.924 --> 00:02:47.340
We were delighted
with the amount.

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:49.680
And then we were
drowned in the amount

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:52.620
and we had to flounder
with it a while.

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:56.184
We came up, we hope,
with an optimum solution.

00:02:56.184 --> 00:02:57.600
And then if I have
time, I'm going

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:00.750
to talk about
Caesar as a general.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:04.230
Illustrate some of his skills,
looking at three battles

00:03:04.230 --> 00:03:06.450
that he undertook.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:08.120
In each, his role
is quite different.

00:03:08.120 --> 00:03:09.930
They're quite different battles.

00:03:09.930 --> 00:03:12.810
And the third one, he
didn't write this narrative.

00:03:12.810 --> 00:03:16.260
It was written by an unknown
author who was clearly

00:03:16.260 --> 00:03:18.630
an eyewitness and
very likely is thought

00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:23.560
to be an officer in his
army at that third battle.

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:25.440
I hope we get to
all of them, but I'm

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:28.470
determined to give Kurt
Raaflaub, my colleague

00:03:28.470 --> 00:03:33.030
here, all of his time that
he certainly well deserves.

00:03:33.030 --> 00:03:35.650
So let's talk about
the Landmark books.

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:37.530
It occurred to me
about 30 years ago,

00:03:37.530 --> 00:03:40.410
when I was doing a little
teaching at a place called

00:03:40.410 --> 00:03:41.880
Simon's Rock of Bard College.

00:03:45.690 --> 00:03:49.080
I discovered that my
students had difficulty

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:50.310
dealing with the histories.

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:51.600
They handled Homer.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:54.090
They handled the poetry.

00:03:54.090 --> 00:03:55.835
They handled the
plays, which were often

00:03:55.835 --> 00:03:59.160
very foreign in content.

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:01.920
And they'd come to
Herodotus and Thucydides

00:04:01.920 --> 00:04:03.600
and you'd think, well,
that's duck soup.

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.420
It reads like a history,
which it does because they

00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:08.060
set the paradigm of histories.

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:11.010
We write the way
they wrote history.

00:04:11.010 --> 00:04:14.580
And I would watch with
dismay as one by one,

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:17.250
the eyes of the students
would glaze over.

00:04:17.250 --> 00:04:18.990
And you'd see that
they were lost,

00:04:18.990 --> 00:04:20.490
and they couldn't
keep up with it,

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:24.720
and didn't know from where this
happened and why that happened.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:28.800
And I decided that it was a
problem of the two editions

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:32.820
that we had for students,
Modern Library and Penguin.

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:36.010
Those are both very
good translations.

00:04:36.010 --> 00:04:38.700
But in the volume, they
are simply black pages.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:41.670
As Bruce said, there are
no appendices worth a damn.

00:04:41.670 --> 00:04:45.030
The maps are in the back,
a little section where

00:04:45.030 --> 00:04:47.910
pretty soon you stop going
because the names on the maps

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:51.540
are not spelled the same way
as the names in the text.

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:54.030
And so you're never sure
if this is the right place.

00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:56.280
And what's more, some
of them are modern maps

00:04:56.280 --> 00:04:57.870
and the places have moved.

00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:02.640
And in a lot of ways, they're
just less help than harm.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:05.070
And most students,
I think, just stop

00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:07.170
using them because they're
difficult to get to

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:11.070
and they provide little in the
way of additional information.

00:05:11.070 --> 00:05:12.840
And in addition,
there are things

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:15.780
that go on in the ancient world
which puzzled modern readers.

00:05:15.780 --> 00:05:16.320
Why not?

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:22.330
What can they be expected to
know about a religion that

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:23.850
has animal sacrifice?

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:26.490
It sounds sort of primitive,
and brutal, and nasty.

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:28.260
And certainly, foreign.

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:32.100
Or the problems, let's say, of
a very complex political system

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:36.210
like Rome's political system in
the last years of the Republic.

00:05:36.210 --> 00:05:43.140
Or the problems of running
a boat with the engine being

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:46.770
175 people rowing it who
need to be fed and slept

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:49.170
and all kinds of
things every night.

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:53.400
So these are difficulties that
even the most astute and I

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:57.930
would say well-educated, but not
classics-educated modern reader

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:00.690
is going to need help to
figure out what's going on.

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:05.220
So those gaps in knowledge,
those gaps in culture,

00:06:05.220 --> 00:06:07.320
have to be somehow filled.

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:10.650
And we determined to fill
them in the Landmark books.

00:06:10.650 --> 00:06:12.810
We have explanatory footnotes.

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:14.100
Let me show you this guy here.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:15.810
We'll get to him in a minute.

00:06:15.810 --> 00:06:19.470
We have explanatory footnotes.

00:06:19.470 --> 00:06:23.310
For real questions like, what
is religion in the pagan world,

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:25.620
we have an appendix
in the back--

00:06:25.620 --> 00:06:28.410
In this case, not in the
back, but on the web--

00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:32.610
that the reader can go to get
as much information as he wants.

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:35.040
We have maps that
are clear and that

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:36.900
are embedded in the
text within a page

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:41.940
or two of the relevant sections
that they are supporting.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:43.590
So there's no going to the back.

00:06:43.590 --> 00:06:46.230
We have illustrations
also embedded.

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:47.880
Not to be pretty, as you'll see.

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:49.190
I'll show you a few of them.

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:50.746
Although, some of
them are pretty.

00:06:50.746 --> 00:06:51.870
But they're not adornments.

00:06:51.870 --> 00:06:55.570
They're there to emphasize
the historicity of the text.

00:06:55.570 --> 00:06:59.610
This is not a
Tolkien fairy tale.

00:06:59.610 --> 00:07:03.630
There were no dragons and
there were no flying elephants.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:08.737
These events really happened
to people who fought and died

00:07:08.737 --> 00:07:11.070
and didn't know in the morning
what was going to happen,

00:07:11.070 --> 00:07:13.110
just as you don't know
in the morning what's

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:15.530
going to happen particularly.

00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:20.390
And they suffered, and
planned, and did all the things

00:07:20.390 --> 00:07:22.580
that you do in their way.

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:24.980
And it is a true story.

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:25.595
It is real.

00:07:28.730 --> 00:07:31.070
It's important to
impress students

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:33.734
with that because it's
all too easy to begin

00:07:33.734 --> 00:07:35.900
to think with these foreign
names and foreign places

00:07:35.900 --> 00:07:39.040
and strange goings on,
I'll just get a good exam.

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:41.540
I don't have to worry
about it too much.

00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:43.010
That's a mistake.

00:07:43.010 --> 00:07:45.170
If you lose the
sense of historicity,

00:07:45.170 --> 00:07:49.790
you've lost half of the
value of these books.

00:07:49.790 --> 00:07:51.650
That's my personal opinion.

00:07:51.650 --> 00:07:55.460
In any case, we give all
kinds of other supports.

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:57.770
We have, as I mentioned,
the appendices.

00:07:57.770 --> 00:07:59.220
We have a glossary.

00:07:59.220 --> 00:08:01.480
We have a very rich index.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:04.490
And we have a
strong introduction

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:06.200
to tell you about the writer.

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:07.790
Of course, in
Caesar's case, it only

00:08:07.790 --> 00:08:09.514
can partially tell
you about the writer

00:08:09.514 --> 00:08:11.180
because there's so
much you can't put it

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:14.480
into an introductory
section of a book.

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:19.650
But we put as much
into it as we can.

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:21.834
Whenever we think
there's something here

00:08:21.834 --> 00:08:23.750
that will cause somebody's
brow to wrinkle up,

00:08:23.750 --> 00:08:26.780
what does that mean,
we try to fix it

00:08:26.780 --> 00:08:29.060
with a footnote
that explains it.

00:08:29.060 --> 00:08:31.220
A footnote that tells
them where to go.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:34.460
Let me show you a page.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.679
You see, it's the text.

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:39.960
There are side notes for each
chapter, which explain where it

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:42.140
took place, when it took place.

00:08:42.140 --> 00:08:44.840
You'd be amazed at how Penguin
and Modern Library don't have

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:47.990
dates for a history of a war.

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:51.650
And then, a little write-up
of where it is because people

00:08:51.650 --> 00:08:55.070
need to come back to this book
and figure out where they were.

00:08:55.070 --> 00:08:57.460
Because if you've
partied all weekend,

00:08:57.460 --> 00:09:01.160
as students do, or even just had
to put it down for two weeks,

00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:03.560
as people do, you
come back and you

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:05.870
want to be able to find
out where you were before.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:07.250
These things help you.

00:09:07.250 --> 00:09:10.060
These footnotes are-- you
can't read them, unfortunately.

00:09:10.060 --> 00:09:11.810
Down here, you can see
there's a reference

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:15.710
to letters to his brother
Quintus by Cicero.

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:18.450
Quintus was in Caesar's army.

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:21.200
And we learn about
some of the things that

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:23.210
were going on in Caesar's
army from the things

00:09:23.210 --> 00:09:24.599
that Quintus
wrote-- his brother.

00:09:24.599 --> 00:09:27.140
And particularly, we learn a
few dates because they're dated.

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:29.420
Quintus wrote on
the 17th of June.

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:31.910
And so that helps us
to establish dates.

00:09:31.910 --> 00:09:33.370
Up here is one of those--

00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:38.000
a reference to Cantium,
which is modern Kent.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:39.240
Map 519.

00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:41.840
Map 519 is right
around the corner.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:47.580
And here is a coin from
Cantium minted by a king--

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:49.430
a king named Tasciovanus.

00:09:49.430 --> 00:09:52.160
But we don't know anything
about him except his coins.

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:56.000
But it's there, again, to
emphasize that this is real.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.020
He mentions this place.

00:09:57.020 --> 00:10:01.840
And there's some practical
evidence that it exists.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:03.680
Now, I talked about maps.

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:05.780
I could show you
some other maps that

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:09.680
are horrible in the Penguin
and the Modern Library.

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:12.380
These you can't
really see very well,

00:10:12.380 --> 00:10:17.510
but the purpose is we
have a locator map, which

00:10:17.510 --> 00:10:19.790
shows Italy, Britain, and Gaul.

00:10:19.790 --> 00:10:22.757
And in the outline is
where this is taking place.

00:10:22.757 --> 00:10:23.840
So you're always oriented.

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:24.780
You know where it is.

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:29.750
In effect, this
is a campaign map.

00:10:29.750 --> 00:10:34.100
Caesar is dividing about
14 campaigns, more or less.

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:37.670
And in the beginning of each
one, we have a campaign map.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:41.720
And this one, in fact, is
his first campaign in 48 BC.

00:10:41.720 --> 00:10:44.290
He comes running up, A--

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:46.460
and you can follow the
alphabetic letters--

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:49.490
from Cisalpine Gaul, where he
has his winter headquarters.

00:10:49.490 --> 00:10:54.020
B, he massacres
the [? Titarini ?]

00:10:54.020 --> 00:10:55.580
crossing the river Aras.

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:59.900
And it tells you where in
the text you can find this.

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:03.050
It says here, this is 4--

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:03.830
I don't know-- 26.

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:05.660
Hard to read.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:11.270
It means it's in chapter
4, Section 26, Bibracte.

00:11:11.270 --> 00:11:14.120
He defeats the Helvetii.

00:11:14.120 --> 00:11:18.260
Here, he catches up with them
and forces their surrender.

00:11:18.260 --> 00:11:21.760
And now he goes after
Ariovistus, the German.

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:23.590
And Ariovistus is here.

00:11:23.590 --> 00:11:24.830
Caesar marches on him--

00:11:24.830 --> 00:11:28.280
I'm encapsulating a
lot-- wins a victory,

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:30.830
defeats him, and takes
his army from F to G

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:33.080
back to Vizantio for
winter headquarters.

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:35.324
That's what you're going
to read in the book.

00:11:35.324 --> 00:11:36.240
And then you go ahead.

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:39.920
There are maps within the
text of the book supporting

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:43.040
what happens in an expanded
way, so that there's

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:44.660
more data, more detail.

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:46.530
But you can always
refer back to this

00:11:46.530 --> 00:11:49.190
to find out what was going
to happen next, or whatever.

00:11:49.190 --> 00:11:51.260
It's useful to understand.

00:11:51.260 --> 00:11:53.230
This is an easy one I picked.

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:55.220
Some of them get pretty
complicated because he

00:11:55.220 --> 00:12:00.560
tended to run all over,
go back and over his path.

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:02.360
And in order not
to make them look

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:05.000
like spaghetti running
back and forth,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.990
we had to do some
particular tricks.

00:12:08.990 --> 00:12:12.200
In one case in book 7 where
there's a great revolt

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.500
and he spends a lot of
time running all over Gaul,

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:16.960
we had two campaign maps
because there was no other way

00:12:16.960 --> 00:12:18.490
to show it.

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:21.350
Here's another map that
we'll explain a little bit.

00:12:21.350 --> 00:12:23.800
It's very hard for you
to see, but here's Rome.

00:12:23.800 --> 00:12:26.480
Here's the coast of
Italy on this map.

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:29.800
Here's the upper Adriatic and
the Adriatic on the other side.

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:34.150
Caesar comes down from Rome
and goes to Brundisium,

00:12:34.150 --> 00:12:35.860
chases Pompey out.

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:38.890
And then later, he comes
back to Brundisium,

00:12:38.890 --> 00:12:42.220
and he crosses over the
Adriatic to Palaesta.

00:12:42.220 --> 00:12:46.720
Now, the telescoping here is
to accomplish different scales

00:12:46.720 --> 00:12:48.520
so that you can show detail.

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:52.330
If we put all these places
at this scale over here

00:12:52.330 --> 00:12:54.070
on the Adriatic,
it would just be

00:12:54.070 --> 00:12:55.285
a bunch of dots all together.

00:12:55.285 --> 00:12:57.160
And you'd have trouble
putting the labels on.

00:12:57.160 --> 00:12:58.493
You'd have trouble reading them.

00:12:58.493 --> 00:13:00.220
You would not, in
effect, have been

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:02.420
imparted any real information.

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:04.390
So in order to
make that clear, we

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:07.240
had another-- a
third telescope map.

00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:09.220
This is the square
that shows it.

00:13:09.220 --> 00:13:10.120
And here it is.

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:12.760
And at least you now
know that Bouthroton

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:16.960
is at approximately 80
miles from Apollonia.

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:19.095
And you could never
meaningfully show that.

00:13:19.095 --> 00:13:20.470
So that's the kind
of thing we do

00:13:20.470 --> 00:13:23.880
to try to make the maps
as clear as possible.

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:27.160
There's no extraneous
stuff on these maps.

00:13:27.160 --> 00:13:30.265
It's only the labels that
are shown in the text, that

00:13:30.265 --> 00:13:31.690
are described in the text.

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:35.060
We try to keep it as
simple as possible.

00:13:35.060 --> 00:13:38.500
This is a map I really love,
and we'll come back to it.

00:13:38.500 --> 00:13:40.900
It's a campaign in
a way of its own.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:43.120
Caesar-- you won't
believe this, but he

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:45.430
suffered some serious defeats.

00:13:45.430 --> 00:13:50.170
In the vicinity of Dyrrachium,
Pompey beat him badly.

00:13:50.170 --> 00:13:53.350
And he caused heavy
casualties into his army.

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:56.980
And Caesar then withdrew
south, skillfully

00:13:56.980 --> 00:14:00.520
withdrew from Pompey.

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:03.160
Pompey chased him, but
couldn't catch up with him.

00:14:03.160 --> 00:14:06.010
And then Pompey turned
back and went down

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:10.270
the main road, the Via
Egnatia, on his way

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:15.160
to meet Scipio, who
was Pompeian, up

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:17.710
and to head for Pharsalus.

00:14:17.710 --> 00:14:21.700
Caesar went south and
had some adventures

00:14:21.700 --> 00:14:24.070
here with two cities,
Gomphi and Metropolis,

00:14:24.070 --> 00:14:25.360
and ended at Pharsalus.

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:27.250
So it ends up with
the two of them

00:14:27.250 --> 00:14:29.080
facing each other at Pharsalus.

00:14:29.080 --> 00:14:32.230
Caesar offering battle
and Pompey refusing it.

00:14:32.230 --> 00:14:35.030
One little side thing
I should mention.

00:14:35.030 --> 00:14:38.830
There was a general,
a Caesarean general,

00:14:38.830 --> 00:14:40.750
with two veteran
legions which would

00:14:40.750 --> 00:14:43.390
have been very important
to Caesar, who didn't know

00:14:43.390 --> 00:14:45.040
anything about that defeat.

00:14:45.040 --> 00:14:47.150
Caesar's attempts to
reach him with a courier

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:48.700
didn't get through.

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:51.280
And he's marching
up the Via Egnatia

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:54.490
when his scouts inform him--

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:55.990
and it's an interesting
way they do.

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:58.870
But they're Gauls, and they
run into their brother Gauls,

00:14:58.870 --> 00:15:00.790
who are scouting for Pompey.

00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:04.270
And they find out he's four
hours' march away from Pompey

00:15:04.270 --> 00:15:07.170
coming down the Via
Egnatia with nine legions.

00:15:07.170 --> 00:15:08.630
He has two.

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:12.040
So that showed how abruptly
he gets out of there.

00:15:12.040 --> 00:15:15.270
And he goes south and
meets Caesar at Aegenium

00:15:15.270 --> 00:15:17.120
and on into Pharsalus.

00:15:17.120 --> 00:15:20.890
So I think it's
an engagement map.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:22.590
And all of these
notes down here,

00:15:22.590 --> 00:15:24.970
some of which you can
see, explain what's going

00:15:24.970 --> 00:15:27.090
on in the A, B, C, Ds and E's.

00:15:27.090 --> 00:15:30.790
But-- oh, here's a
picture of what the Via

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:32.120
Egnatia looks like today.

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:33.340
A section of it.

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:35.489
So Pompey might have been there.

00:15:35.489 --> 00:15:36.780
Domitius might have been there.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:37.760
Well, Pompey
certainly was there.

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:39.010
He went the whole way.

00:15:39.010 --> 00:15:43.810
So this is a way of explaining
a very complex maneuver of two

00:15:43.810 --> 00:15:47.530
armies that Caesar's
description is difficult to go

00:15:47.530 --> 00:15:48.530
because it's going back.

00:15:48.530 --> 00:15:50.440
Meanwhile, back at the so--

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:52.210
and so it goes back and forth.

00:15:52.210 --> 00:15:55.390
And it takes some real analysis
to figure out what's going on.

00:15:55.390 --> 00:15:57.550
Believe me, that
map helps a lot.

00:15:57.550 --> 00:16:01.810
Now, here's an illustration
that I think, in fact,

00:16:01.810 --> 00:16:03.790
is quite beautiful.

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:05.255
It shows a slinger.

00:16:05.255 --> 00:16:06.510
He's not a Roman, probably.

00:16:06.510 --> 00:16:07.870
Probably, a Gaul.

00:16:07.870 --> 00:16:11.320
Or certainly, somebody
in Italy who is not--

00:16:11.320 --> 00:16:12.580
an Italian who's not Roman.

00:16:12.580 --> 00:16:17.170
Very possibly, slingers came
from Numidia or from Crete.

00:16:17.170 --> 00:16:18.490
So he could be one of these.

00:16:18.490 --> 00:16:19.660
And he's about to throw--

00:16:19.660 --> 00:16:20.875
he's surrounded with others.

00:16:20.875 --> 00:16:22.750
This one's just going
to throw with his hand.

00:16:22.750 --> 00:16:27.340
And he's got his weapons
there, his ammunition.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:31.600
And over here, it goes on
to show somebody firing

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:33.580
a scorpion.

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:35.890
And that's the
ammunition lined up

00:16:35.890 --> 00:16:40.150
for a scorpion, which
is a small catapult.

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:41.470
That's a pretty picture.

00:16:41.470 --> 00:16:44.600
This next one gives
you verisimilitude

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:46.150
and the historicity.

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:51.340
These are two wire
containers, as you can

00:16:51.340 --> 00:16:53.980
scale by the gentleman there.

00:16:53.980 --> 00:16:56.410
They're at Uxellodunum,
the last battle

00:16:56.410 --> 00:17:00.130
that Caesar fought in Gaul.

00:17:00.130 --> 00:17:04.839
And they contain literally
thousands of sling stones

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:06.940
that were gathered from
the battlefield, which

00:17:06.940 --> 00:17:08.380
is not a big area.

00:17:08.380 --> 00:17:10.880
Believe me, it wasn't as
big as the campus here.

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:15.240
And piled up just to
see how many there were.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:16.210
And one wasn't enough.

00:17:16.210 --> 00:17:17.790
They had to get
another container.

00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:19.980
And I don't think
it's been counted,

00:17:19.980 --> 00:17:21.690
but there are thousands of them.

00:17:21.690 --> 00:17:26.220
And it indicates the scale of
how this ammunition was used,

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:29.160
even in what was a relatively
small battle in a fairly

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:30.450
confined space.

00:17:30.450 --> 00:17:32.010
Part of a siege.

00:17:32.010 --> 00:17:35.610
So if you see this, you know
that that's not a fairy tale.

00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:36.690
There they are.

00:17:36.690 --> 00:17:39.231
There are the stones that people
were throwing at each other.

00:17:41.309 --> 00:17:43.600
Before I go on with this, I
want to talk about the fact

00:17:43.600 --> 00:17:48.190
that the format of
the Landmark series

00:17:48.190 --> 00:17:53.320
ran into a tremendous
amount of data about Caesar.

00:17:53.320 --> 00:17:56.545
There are five extant,
ancient, contemporary,

00:17:56.545 --> 00:17:58.930
or almost contemporary sources--

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:02.830
historians, whose work we have--
and they wrote about Caesar.

00:18:02.830 --> 00:18:05.750
And there's just about nobody
else in the ancient world

00:18:05.750 --> 00:18:07.510
that we have that
much material on.

00:18:07.510 --> 00:18:10.600
Plus you have all
kinds of letters

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:14.410
from Cicero, to his brother,
to Atticus, to various people.

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:16.390
There are letters
from Cicero to Caesar.

00:18:16.390 --> 00:18:19.870
And letters from
Caesar back to Cicero.

00:18:19.870 --> 00:18:21.350
There's not a lot, but some.

00:18:21.350 --> 00:18:23.780
So that, again, they
must be real people.

00:18:23.780 --> 00:18:25.330
They say, how is
your daughter doing?

00:18:25.330 --> 00:18:26.950
I understand she was sick.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:29.770
Well, that's personal.

00:18:29.770 --> 00:18:31.630
And it makes it
clear that these were

00:18:31.630 --> 00:18:35.840
people talking to each other
and not some historic document.

00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:38.340
But we learn lots of things
about Caesar from it.

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:40.420
Cicero's letters
often have gossip.

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:44.967
Oh, I heard Caesar was
at Lutetia on the 17th.

00:18:44.967 --> 00:18:47.050
He's supposed to have
suffered a bad defeat, which

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:48.040
we know is not true.

00:18:48.040 --> 00:18:49.270
But that's what Cicero--

00:18:49.270 --> 00:18:51.710
that's the misinformation
that Cicero had at that day.

00:18:51.710 --> 00:18:53.740
And those kind of
things really help

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:55.714
us to understand
and see a continuity

00:18:55.714 --> 00:18:56.630
of what was happening.

00:18:56.630 --> 00:18:59.140
And what it looked like
in Rome, because Cicero

00:18:59.140 --> 00:19:00.710
stayed in Rome when all--

00:19:00.710 --> 00:19:04.060
or at least at home in
Arpinum during all this time.

00:19:07.750 --> 00:19:10.210
This is to show you--

00:19:10.210 --> 00:19:11.890
well, I'm not going
to get to this yet.

00:19:11.890 --> 00:19:13.150
Let me go back again.

00:19:13.150 --> 00:19:16.900
We had so much data, we did not
know how to put it together.

00:19:16.900 --> 00:19:22.630
I knew as Kurt came up with more
and more ideas for appendices

00:19:22.630 --> 00:19:24.700
that we were running
over what we would have.

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:27.460
But I assumed, frankly,
as the series editor,

00:19:27.460 --> 00:19:31.150
that we'd find a way to
reduce the size as we

00:19:31.150 --> 00:19:32.965
had done in previous editions.

00:19:36.110 --> 00:19:38.950
Another problem is as you're
doing one of these books,

00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:41.290
you don't know how many
pages you've accrued.

00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:44.080
Your 8-by-11 type
script does not at all

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:46.570
represent how many
pages you have.

00:19:46.570 --> 00:19:49.000
So it wasn't until
we finished and we

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.570
had it paginated by the genius
lady, Kim Llewellyn, who

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:56.720
makes these pages work
and be attractive even.

00:19:56.720 --> 00:19:59.080
Being attractive is
not trivial for a book

00:19:59.080 --> 00:20:03.650
that you want the lay readers
to delve into and find

00:20:03.650 --> 00:20:05.050
useful and interesting.

00:20:05.050 --> 00:20:08.050
So in order to
have it paginated,

00:20:08.050 --> 00:20:09.160
she worked hard on it.

00:20:09.160 --> 00:20:14.270
And we came out with
1,350 to 1,400 pages.

00:20:14.270 --> 00:20:15.220
Now, a trade book--

00:20:15.220 --> 00:20:16.136
I don't have one here.

00:20:16.136 --> 00:20:17.780
I was sure one would be here.

00:20:17.780 --> 00:20:20.860
But a trade book is
about this thick.

00:20:20.860 --> 00:20:24.490
About 950 to 1,000 pages
is all it can accommodate.

00:20:24.490 --> 00:20:27.370
So I went to the publisher
and I said, can we

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:28.360
do a second volume?

00:20:28.360 --> 00:20:29.560
And he said, absolutely not.

00:20:29.560 --> 00:20:31.180
And I think he's right.

00:20:31.180 --> 00:20:34.660
You're not going to get two
volumes bought, of which one

00:20:34.660 --> 00:20:37.330
is only essays about Caesar.

00:20:37.330 --> 00:20:40.570
So we had to come up
with another solution.

00:20:40.570 --> 00:20:43.840
To make a long story
short, we went to the web.

00:20:43.840 --> 00:20:45.550
It's the only place we could go.

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:49.930
It was a brilliant solution,
but the only solution possible.

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:54.520
So some 40 appendices,
now called web essays,

00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:56.861
are still an integral
part of the book.

00:20:56.861 --> 00:20:58.360
You still have a
footnote there that

00:20:58.360 --> 00:21:04.000
says see web essay L for
stuff about Lucius so-and-so.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.750
And you can go to it
with a few finger clicks.

00:21:07.750 --> 00:21:10.150
Or you can take
down the appendices

00:21:10.150 --> 00:21:12.760
and download them yourself
to your own computer.

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:18.130
Or you can take them down to a
disk or you can print them out.

00:21:18.130 --> 00:21:20.290
So they're all very
accessible to you.

00:21:20.290 --> 00:21:23.800
And they're even accessible to
people who don't read our book

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:25.830
and don't buy it
because it's on the web

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:28.360
and we're not going to try to
code it and make it difficult.

00:21:28.360 --> 00:21:29.840
It's fine if they get it.

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:32.590
Our goal is to-- we're hoping
if somebody does that, they'll

00:21:32.590 --> 00:21:34.330
end up buying the book because
they'll want to know where

00:21:34.330 --> 00:21:35.560
these things came from.

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:41.050
But basically, what we have
here is almost 30% of the book

00:21:41.050 --> 00:21:42.520
is not printed.

00:21:42.520 --> 00:21:46.300
It's not in the book because
of the printed medium's

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:48.160
limitations.

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:50.940
We couldn't get in one
volume all of the material.

00:21:50.940 --> 00:21:53.910
And I was reluctant
to really cut it hard

00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:57.010
because once I read them
all with that intention,

00:21:57.010 --> 00:21:58.850
they were extremely good essays.

00:21:58.850 --> 00:22:02.740
As a body, they formed
a terrific amount

00:22:02.740 --> 00:22:04.590
of supplementary
material for somebody

00:22:04.590 --> 00:22:07.660
who's interested in learning
about Caesar in his time.

00:22:07.660 --> 00:22:10.300
And Caesar's time was one of
those interesting moments.

00:22:10.300 --> 00:22:15.587
A 500-year government is
breaking down, breaking apart.

00:22:15.587 --> 00:22:17.920
When we started, we didn't
think there was any relevance

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:19.630
to that, to our modern day.

00:22:19.630 --> 00:22:21.580
But right now,
there are people who

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:23.890
suspect that the
American government is

00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:26.170
in a situation where
norms are being stretched

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:28.990
and things don't
look like the way

00:22:28.990 --> 00:22:31.030
they did 10 or 20 years ago.

00:22:31.030 --> 00:22:34.210
And it's conceivable
that, in fact, this

00:22:34.210 --> 00:22:36.460
is part of a
process that's going

00:22:36.460 --> 00:22:38.780
to end with a major
change in the government.

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:43.090
I don't know, but there
are parallel items,

00:22:43.090 --> 00:22:48.160
stretches of the norms in
Caesar and going on today.

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:52.920
So let's now turn to the
maps and the battlefields.

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:54.800
This-- I know you
can't see where it is.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:57.760
It's in the central,
northwest of--

00:22:57.760 --> 00:22:58.910
northeast of Paris.

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:00.460
Paris is about here somewhere.

00:23:00.460 --> 00:23:02.230
And up here on the
Sambre River is

00:23:02.230 --> 00:23:05.640
where Caesar has a major
battle with the Nervii

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:08.660
tribe, a major Belgian--

00:23:08.660 --> 00:23:10.630
Belgae, it's called--

00:23:10.630 --> 00:23:12.220
Gallic tribe.

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:17.320
And it's the only
instance I know of where

00:23:17.320 --> 00:23:19.250
he's taken by surprise.

00:23:19.250 --> 00:23:24.430
He's informed that the Nervii
and their allies are here.

00:23:24.430 --> 00:23:26.320
He comes up here
to build a camp.

00:23:26.320 --> 00:23:28.900
Everybody pitches in
to build the camp.

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:31.750
When suddenly, out
of the nearby woods

00:23:31.750 --> 00:23:35.780
come the Atrebates, the
Viromandui, and the Nervii.

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:36.800
And he writes about it.

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:38.800
Says, they came down the
hill, across the river,

00:23:38.800 --> 00:23:41.830
and up the hill so fast, it was
like it all happened at once.

00:23:41.830 --> 00:23:48.550
And his Latin was probably
much, much swifter than that.

00:23:48.550 --> 00:23:52.270
And in the next part of his
writing, it's an absolute--

00:23:52.270 --> 00:23:54.940
maybe one of the best, if
not the best description

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:56.440
of an ancient battle.

00:23:56.440 --> 00:23:58.850
Because he describes
what he had to do.

00:23:58.850 --> 00:24:02.290
He gives tribute to the
soldiers that if they weren't

00:24:02.290 --> 00:24:04.600
by their own unit, they
fell in line in nearby units

00:24:04.600 --> 00:24:06.669
because their training was good.

00:24:06.669 --> 00:24:08.710
Some of them had no time
to put their helmets on.

00:24:08.710 --> 00:24:12.220
They couldn't take-- the shields
are carried in a shield cover.

00:24:12.220 --> 00:24:13.780
They couldn't take
the covers off.

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:16.630
And so they are really
under assault suddenly

00:24:16.630 --> 00:24:18.760
and without preparation.

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:20.200
And they're surprised.

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:22.420
And they could have
been overwhelmed.

00:24:22.420 --> 00:24:24.730
But being Roman soldiers,
they fall into line

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:26.170
and they start the battle.

00:24:26.170 --> 00:24:28.390
He goes to the 10th Legion,
which is his favorite,

00:24:28.390 --> 00:24:29.930
and starts as he says.

00:24:29.930 --> 00:24:34.180
And he gives them a pep talk
and sends them across the river.

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:36.610
The 11th and 8th
Legion deal with--

00:24:36.610 --> 00:24:39.700
I'll show you the next slide--
deal with the Viromandui.

00:24:39.700 --> 00:24:42.520
But the crisis forms
here on the Roman right,

00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:46.180
where the 7th and 12th Legion
are overwhelmed and almost

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:48.350
encircled by the Nervii.

00:24:51.010 --> 00:24:54.530
Here's the 9th and 10th
having defeated the Atrebates.

00:24:54.530 --> 00:24:58.970
The 11th and 8th have stabilized
and held off the Viromandui.

00:24:58.970 --> 00:25:02.630
But the Nervii are
getting around the 7th

00:25:02.630 --> 00:25:04.460
and threatening the 12th.

00:25:04.460 --> 00:25:08.660
And entering even the
half-built Roman camp.

00:25:08.660 --> 00:25:10.760
And normally, if you
enter the enemy's camp,

00:25:10.760 --> 00:25:11.979
you win the battle.

00:25:11.979 --> 00:25:13.520
Because the enemy
soldiers don't want

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:16.640
to stand by and watch all their
belongings and their slaves

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:18.530
or their women
and their servants

00:25:18.530 --> 00:25:20.540
and their private
stuff get taken away.

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:23.870
And they go running off
the line to protect that.

00:25:23.870 --> 00:25:25.547
That wouldn't be
the total case here,

00:25:25.547 --> 00:25:27.380
partly because Romans
were very disciplined.

00:25:27.380 --> 00:25:29.660
And partly because the
camp not being completed,

00:25:29.660 --> 00:25:33.080
probably didn't have all of
those accoutrements in it.

00:25:33.080 --> 00:25:35.006
But there still
was a chance that--

00:25:35.006 --> 00:25:36.380
Caesar says when
he got there, he

00:25:36.380 --> 00:25:38.060
saw the men clumping
together, which

00:25:38.060 --> 00:25:40.460
is a very bad thing for
the kind of warfare it is.

00:25:40.460 --> 00:25:44.180
You have to have space for
people to use their weapons.

00:25:44.180 --> 00:25:48.020
He saw some of them wavering and
beginning to head to the rear.

00:25:48.020 --> 00:25:55.010
He saw confusion and
so many of the officers

00:25:55.010 --> 00:25:57.140
killed that there was
actually a lack in some

00:25:57.140 --> 00:25:59.940
of the units of direction.

00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:03.380
And so-- he only did
this twice, I think--

00:26:03.380 --> 00:26:05.960
he grabs a shield
from a soldier.

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:08.330
And probably with
his red cloak, he's

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:10.190
very-- that's a general's cloak.

00:26:10.190 --> 00:26:11.390
He's very visible.

00:26:11.390 --> 00:26:13.430
He runs up to the
front line and he

00:26:13.430 --> 00:26:20.990
calls on the centurions, who
are the sergeants of the era.

00:26:20.990 --> 00:26:26.090
And he calls them by name to
come and to give direction

00:26:26.090 --> 00:26:28.600
and put the lines together.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:32.810
And I figured out that there
were eight legions in his army,

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:36.080
and there are 60 centurions
in each army-- each legion.

00:26:36.080 --> 00:26:40.280
And so we can assume he had
480 to 500 centurions, which

00:26:40.280 --> 00:26:41.944
he knew by name.

00:26:41.944 --> 00:26:44.360
And I think I read somewhere
that he had a fabulous memory

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:45.680
for things like that.

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:48.710
And here's a case where he
used that to good effect

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:49.730
as a general.

00:26:49.730 --> 00:26:53.720
In the end, he put the
12th Legion behind the 7th.

00:26:53.720 --> 00:26:56.160
He moved it, flitted
over, faced it around

00:26:56.160 --> 00:26:59.820
so it was facing this way, which
was stopping the encirclement.

00:26:59.820 --> 00:27:05.060
And at least protected
the 7th from the rear.

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:09.560
Labienus was on the hill here,
the general of the 10th Legion.

00:27:09.560 --> 00:27:12.239
And he saw what was happening,
and he sent the 10th Legion

00:27:12.239 --> 00:27:14.030
all across the battlefield
here, which went

00:27:14.030 --> 00:27:16.130
to the flank of the Nervii.

00:27:16.130 --> 00:27:18.830
And these two, which were
green recruit legions,

00:27:18.830 --> 00:27:21.830
had been used only to
accompany the baggage.

00:27:21.830 --> 00:27:24.680
Their appearance
on the scene was

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:28.700
enough to give the Nervii
pause because they were there

00:27:28.700 --> 00:27:30.410
in the flank and the rear.

00:27:30.410 --> 00:27:33.650
So basically, the
battle was stabilized.

00:27:33.650 --> 00:27:35.570
The Romans when they
got a stabilized battle,

00:27:35.570 --> 00:27:39.380
they could fight the Germans
and the Gauls to a finish

00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:42.230
because they had a better
means of replacement,

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:44.400
and better weapons,
and better tactics.

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:46.670
And so it ended up
with just butchery.

00:27:46.670 --> 00:27:48.140
Caesar does say
that the Germans--

00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:50.270
that the Nervii
just kept coming.

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:53.690
They would climb now the
rampart that the dead bodies

00:27:53.690 --> 00:27:55.730
of their compatriots
formed and be

00:27:55.730 --> 00:27:58.320
fighting from above with
them until they were killed.

00:27:58.320 --> 00:28:00.756
And then, new ones stepped
up, until the day was over

00:28:00.756 --> 00:28:01.880
and most of them were dead.

00:28:04.470 --> 00:28:08.330
He ends that their reputation
for valor was justified.

00:28:08.330 --> 00:28:09.650
OK.

00:28:09.650 --> 00:28:13.650
That's one battle which shows
him operating in an emergency.

00:28:13.650 --> 00:28:15.740
You've got to remember,
this is his second year

00:28:15.740 --> 00:28:16.970
of his campaigning.

00:28:16.970 --> 00:28:19.550
He doesn't have the seven
years where these guys--

00:28:19.550 --> 00:28:21.170
where he's a successful general.

00:28:21.170 --> 00:28:22.880
He's made them all rich.

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:25.970
They're completely
devoted to him.

00:28:25.970 --> 00:28:28.490
He had to really show what
he could do here in order

00:28:28.490 --> 00:28:31.460
to save this situation.

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:35.360
His main opponent was a
former military genius,

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:37.440
a Roman one named Pompey.

00:28:37.440 --> 00:28:40.670
And here the two of them are.

00:28:40.670 --> 00:28:44.480
And as I mentioned before,
at Dyrrachium Pompey defeated

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:47.930
Caesar rather handily.

00:28:47.930 --> 00:28:49.670
Caesar made an error here.

00:28:49.670 --> 00:28:50.480
Two of them.

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:52.820
He left open a part
of a fortification,

00:28:52.820 --> 00:28:54.530
which he should have closed.

00:28:54.530 --> 00:28:57.740
He didn't blame himself, but
he should have blamed himself.

00:28:57.740 --> 00:29:00.350
And then he saw an opportunity
for a counterattack,

00:29:00.350 --> 00:29:01.610
which was risky.

00:29:01.610 --> 00:29:04.910
And he sent his men into it and
they got lost in the terrain.

00:29:04.910 --> 00:29:08.060
They had not really
reconnoitered it well enough.

00:29:08.060 --> 00:29:09.950
And they broke down some walls--

00:29:09.950 --> 00:29:12.080
holes in walls, so
they could get through.

00:29:12.080 --> 00:29:15.080
And when Pompey counterattacked
and they needed to retreat,

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:18.370
those holes in the walls
became choke points.

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:20.300
And so many of their
casualties were men

00:29:20.300 --> 00:29:22.440
being trampled as others fled.

00:29:22.440 --> 00:29:25.380
The cavalry also tried
to get back through them.

00:29:25.380 --> 00:29:26.900
It was a disaster.

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:31.340
And right away, Caesar
had to break the siege.

00:29:31.340 --> 00:29:32.900
Here's that map again.

00:29:32.900 --> 00:29:36.860
Caesar went down south,
avoided Pompey's pursuit.

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:40.550
And then they went on
their ways to Pharsalus.

00:29:40.550 --> 00:29:43.850
And I mentioned at Pharsalus,
for a few days there--

00:29:43.850 --> 00:29:45.065
we don't know how many days--

00:29:45.065 --> 00:29:49.040
Caesar would offer battle and
Pompey wouldn't accept it.

00:29:49.040 --> 00:29:51.230
Pompey knew that
his troops would not

00:29:51.230 --> 00:29:53.870
stand up to Caesar's, even
though Pompey had twice as

00:29:53.870 --> 00:29:54.680
many.

00:29:54.680 --> 00:29:57.450
He had Roman recruits
and Greek recruits.

00:29:57.450 --> 00:30:01.650
And Caesar had real veterans
who had been through eight,

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:04.380
nine years of heavy warfare.

00:30:04.380 --> 00:30:06.800
So Pompey didn't want to fight.

00:30:06.800 --> 00:30:11.720
But his men misjudged the nature
of their victory at Dyrrachium.

00:30:11.720 --> 00:30:13.820
They thought they
had won it by--

00:30:17.490 --> 00:30:18.990
how much?

00:30:18.990 --> 00:30:20.300
Zero.

00:30:20.300 --> 00:30:20.985
OK, quickly.

00:30:23.926 --> 00:30:25.800
They thought they had
won it with great skill

00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:28.080
and Caesar was finished.

00:30:28.080 --> 00:30:30.010
And so they wanted to battle.

00:30:30.010 --> 00:30:32.490
Pompey accepted it
with a special plan

00:30:32.490 --> 00:30:37.666
that he was going to use his
cavalry, which he had 7,000

00:30:37.666 --> 00:30:41.280
to about a 1,000 of Caesar's
to overwhelm Caesar's cavalry

00:30:41.280 --> 00:30:42.690
and fight--

00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:44.390
attack the Caesar in the rear.

00:30:44.390 --> 00:30:48.330
Caesar's counter-plan was
to bring a fourth line up

00:30:48.330 --> 00:30:52.230
by calling on cohorts
from his third line.

00:30:52.230 --> 00:30:53.850
And that worked just right.

00:30:53.850 --> 00:30:56.580
They attacked Pompey's
cavalry from the flank.

00:30:56.580 --> 00:30:57.870
They threw them out.

00:30:57.870 --> 00:31:02.490
And then they-- that
is, the fourth line--

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:05.820
walked past Pompey's flank
and attacked the rear.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:09.290
Caesar sent his third line
in and Pompey's troops broke.

00:31:09.290 --> 00:31:11.040
And it was a major victory.

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:14.280
Here I just say he's
a major tactician.

00:31:14.280 --> 00:31:16.180
He foresaw what was
going to happen.

00:31:16.180 --> 00:31:19.290
He organized his troops,
a successful counter.

00:31:19.290 --> 00:31:22.540
His role was just to set it in
motion and watch what happened,

00:31:22.540 --> 00:31:23.880
at least as he describes it.

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:26.280
And it happened pretty
much according to his plan.

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:30.200
But I want to show
you one last picture.

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:30.780
It's a map.

00:31:30.780 --> 00:31:32.100
I don't know if you can see it.

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:33.430
Down here is Egypt.

00:31:33.430 --> 00:31:35.960
Up there is northeastern Turkey.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:40.890
Here's Thessaly,
where Pharsalus was.

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:41.970
Here's the Adriatic.

00:31:41.970 --> 00:31:43.350
Here's Italy.

00:31:43.350 --> 00:31:46.740
Here's Africa, Spain, and Gaul.

00:31:46.740 --> 00:31:49.590
Caesar fought
battles everywhere.

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:54.150
In these 14 years, he was
a general whose chessboard

00:31:54.150 --> 00:31:56.320
was the entire Mediterranean.

00:31:56.320 --> 00:32:00.420
And I leave you with that
thought and this image.

00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:04.321
And I turn it over to my
colleague, Professor Raaflaub.

00:32:04.321 --> 00:32:07.267
