00:33:07.920 --> 00:33:10.470
produced these beautiful maps.

00:33:10.470 --> 00:33:14.010
And the negotiations
behind this, I just

00:33:14.010 --> 00:33:15.250
know that they happened.

00:33:15.250 --> 00:33:20.360
But then, illustrations
and everything else.

00:33:20.360 --> 00:33:22.760
And these specialists
are high-quality people

00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:25.520
who are really committed
to producing these volumes.

00:33:25.520 --> 00:33:30.200
So I could not have done
anything like this on my own.

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:32.840
And I'm very grateful
to Bob and his team,

00:33:32.840 --> 00:33:36.110
that they showed this commitment
and produced this, which

00:33:36.110 --> 00:33:39.860
I think a very useful volume.

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:45.620
I thought I would start by
showing you the difficulties.

00:33:45.620 --> 00:33:49.310
Bob talked about the
difficulties that Caesar posed.

00:33:49.310 --> 00:33:53.030
He wrote his, what
was called Comentarii,

00:33:53.030 --> 00:33:58.010
which is a report on these
Gallic wars, on his own wars.

00:33:58.010 --> 00:34:00.380
But he had literary ambitions.

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:02.980
And he didn't want to
write a general's report.

00:34:02.980 --> 00:34:06.660
Generals give dates and
distances and routes,

00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:07.460
and so on.

00:34:07.460 --> 00:34:09.170
Historians don't.

00:34:09.170 --> 00:34:13.370
And Caesar knew
Thucydides very well,

00:34:13.370 --> 00:34:17.210
so he knew that historians
don't go into these details.

00:34:17.210 --> 00:34:20.690
They show the big outlines,
and the dramatic episodes,

00:34:20.690 --> 00:34:21.409
and so on.

00:34:21.409 --> 00:34:23.420
And that's what
Caesar wanted to do.

00:34:23.420 --> 00:34:28.429
So for us modern scholars
to reconstruct the way

00:34:28.429 --> 00:34:31.429
that Caesar fought
this war in Gaul based

00:34:31.429 --> 00:34:33.840
on his very limited
information that he

00:34:33.840 --> 00:34:37.730
gives in this respect was
sometimes quite difficult.

00:34:37.730 --> 00:34:42.870
And I want to illustrate this
for you with two episodes,

00:34:42.870 --> 00:34:47.810
at both the landings in
Britain in 55 and in 54.

00:34:47.810 --> 00:34:54.020
In 55, he tells us that
he landed three days

00:34:54.020 --> 00:34:56.030
before a full moon night.

00:34:56.030 --> 00:34:58.070
During that night,
the storm combined

00:34:58.070 --> 00:35:02.540
with the springtide heavily
damaged the anchored fleet.

00:35:02.540 --> 00:35:07.910
Now, we know because scientists
have calculated this.

00:35:07.910 --> 00:35:11.060
And we know that the
times of the dates

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:16.790
of full moons and new moons and
equinoxes back to Caesar's time

00:35:16.790 --> 00:35:18.090
and farther back.

00:35:18.090 --> 00:35:21.940
So we know that full moon
nights in the late summer of 55

00:35:21.940 --> 00:35:22.790
were three--

00:35:22.790 --> 00:35:26.750
July 31, August 30,
and September 28.

00:35:26.750 --> 00:35:29.870
And Caesar tells us he
returned to the mainland

00:35:29.870 --> 00:35:32.720
before the equinox,
the fall equinox, which

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:34.580
was on September 26.

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:39.620
So the date for the full moon
of September 28 is too late.

00:35:39.620 --> 00:35:43.600
If we add up, as we
did, all the time Caesar

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:47.120
must have consumed for
his trips before he

00:35:47.120 --> 00:35:53.660
came to the start-off point
for the expedition to Britain,

00:35:53.660 --> 00:35:55.160
you don't see the ocean lines.

00:35:55.160 --> 00:35:57.590
This is very unfortunate,
but that's what it is.

00:35:57.590 --> 00:36:01.250
Here, Portus Itius,
moderne Boulogne-sur-Mer.

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:07.610
And here is Caesar's
departure for Britain.

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:11.480
Before he arrived there,
he did various things,

00:36:11.480 --> 00:36:15.860
crossing Gaul from
west to east and back.

00:36:15.860 --> 00:36:20.360
And so just barely
enough time for him

00:36:20.360 --> 00:36:25.670
to reach the departure
point and to get to Britain.

00:36:25.670 --> 00:36:31.880
So we can say that the July 31
date is absolutely too early.

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:33.050
It cannot have been that.

00:36:33.050 --> 00:36:38.420
That leaves one date, and
that is the August 27,

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:42.170
the full moon, and the
springtide of that date, which

00:36:42.170 --> 00:36:45.500
helps us date precisely
when Caesar actually

00:36:45.500 --> 00:36:47.720
landed in Britain.

00:36:47.720 --> 00:36:51.650
Now, the second case
of the landing in 54

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:55.180
is more interesting
and more complicated.

00:36:55.180 --> 00:36:58.310
Caesar writes he sets
sail around sunset,

00:36:58.310 --> 00:37:02.120
is carried by a southwest wind.

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:04.460
Around midnight, the wind stops.

00:37:04.460 --> 00:37:07.250
The current drives
him far to the east.

00:37:07.250 --> 00:37:11.210
You see that on the map
with the arrow there.

00:37:11.210 --> 00:37:16.555
And then around dawn,
he sees far to the left

00:37:16.555 --> 00:37:18.620
the coast of Britain.

00:37:18.620 --> 00:37:22.190
And then the current changes
and carries him back.

00:37:22.190 --> 00:37:26.450
And when he uses the rows and
he finds the landing's beach

00:37:26.450 --> 00:37:27.860
and is able to land.

00:37:27.860 --> 00:37:30.370
The second night
after his landing,

00:37:30.370 --> 00:37:32.450
there is another huge storm.

00:37:32.450 --> 00:37:36.270
And that again damages
his fleet very heavily.

00:37:36.270 --> 00:37:42.710
The whole army works for 10 days
to repair as many of the ships

00:37:42.710 --> 00:37:43.910
as possible.

00:37:43.910 --> 00:37:48.050
So that's what Caesar
tells us himself.

00:37:48.050 --> 00:37:52.580
Scholars naturally connect
this storm with a full moon

00:37:52.580 --> 00:37:54.500
as it was in the previous year.

00:37:54.500 --> 00:37:57.380
I don't think this could
be because Caesar knew

00:37:57.380 --> 00:37:59.570
that full moons are dangerous.

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:03.160
And so he would have
taken special precautions.

00:38:03.160 --> 00:38:05.810
But anyway, that's what
scholars tend to do.

00:38:05.810 --> 00:38:08.750
Now, Bob mentioned
the correspondence

00:38:08.750 --> 00:38:13.400
between the subcommander,
the deputy commander,

00:38:13.400 --> 00:38:17.195
Quintus Cicero, who
was a subcommander

00:38:17.195 --> 00:38:19.190
in Caesar's army at the time.

00:38:19.190 --> 00:38:23.930
And his brother, the famous
orator, Marcus Tullius Cicero--

00:38:23.930 --> 00:38:28.430
Tully in early
American language--

00:38:28.430 --> 00:38:29.390
in Rome.

00:38:29.390 --> 00:38:34.040
And from this
correspondence, we can

00:38:34.040 --> 00:38:40.280
derive with absolute certainty
that August 2 or 3 in the Roman

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:45.530
calendar system was the latest
possible date for Caesar's

00:38:45.530 --> 00:38:47.990
landing in Britain.

00:38:47.990 --> 00:38:52.160
Hence, the full moon of
August 14 is too late.

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:58.930
But there was a new moon on
the night of July 30, 31.

00:38:58.930 --> 00:39:04.540
And we know that new moon and
full moon are equally liable--

00:39:04.540 --> 00:39:08.170
likely to produce
springtides, so on.

00:39:08.170 --> 00:39:11.140
Now, the pattern
that Caesar describes

00:39:11.140 --> 00:39:17.680
for what happened to him
when he crossed over,

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:22.930
studying these patterns over a
long period of time have found

00:39:22.930 --> 00:39:27.190
applies only to the days
shortly before a full moon

00:39:27.190 --> 00:39:29.410
or a new moon.

00:39:29.410 --> 00:39:33.300
So here is what they sent us.

00:39:33.300 --> 00:39:37.330
We wrote to the National
Oceanographic Institute

00:39:37.330 --> 00:39:40.450
in Liverpool and found
an interested person who

00:39:40.450 --> 00:39:44.170
sent us these illustrations.

00:39:44.170 --> 00:39:47.320
And you see that exactly
what Caesar describes

00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:50.170
happens in these schemes--

00:39:50.170 --> 00:39:54.730
current to the northeast,
current to the southwest

00:39:54.730 --> 00:39:57.430
after 5:00 AM.

00:39:57.430 --> 00:39:58.610
And this is Caesar.

00:39:58.610 --> 00:40:02.770
So we know it had to be
just before a full moon

00:40:02.770 --> 00:40:04.600
or a new moon.

00:40:04.600 --> 00:40:07.330
And so that helps us
because Caesar says two

00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:09.385
days before this, he landed.

00:40:09.385 --> 00:40:12.520
It must have been July 29.

00:40:12.520 --> 00:40:15.730
And again, if we add all
the activities of Caesar

00:40:15.730 --> 00:40:19.910
before then, it couldn't
have been an earlier date.

00:40:19.910 --> 00:40:20.830
So that helps us.

00:40:20.830 --> 00:40:24.100
And this is actually
completely new with certainty

00:40:24.100 --> 00:40:32.600
to date the second landing
on the 29th of July.

00:40:32.600 --> 00:40:33.480
Right?

00:40:33.480 --> 00:40:36.030
Yes.

00:40:36.030 --> 00:40:41.010
Now, Caesar is a
fascinating personality.

00:40:41.010 --> 00:40:45.390
He came from a family
that was very old,

00:40:45.390 --> 00:40:49.380
went back to the beginnings of
Rome, or even to the goddess

00:40:49.380 --> 00:40:54.460
Venus as ancestress
of the family.

00:40:54.460 --> 00:40:56.930
It had lost much of
its luster over time.

00:40:56.930 --> 00:41:00.750
There were no famous
immediate ancestors of Caesar,

00:41:00.750 --> 00:41:03.160
but he belonged to the
highest aristocracy.

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:07.500
And he took that very seriously.

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:13.290
His aunt was the wife of the
famous war hero Gaius Marius.

00:41:13.290 --> 00:41:19.260
And Gaius Marius was a
populist politician in Rome.

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:22.050
In the 80s, there were
civil wars between--

00:41:22.050 --> 00:41:25.830
you may have heard the
name of Sulla and Marius.

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:28.320
And Sulla was a
very conservative

00:41:28.320 --> 00:41:34.200
right-wing politician
who, when he was in power,

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:36.930
ordered Caesar to
divorce his wife,

00:41:36.930 --> 00:41:40.650
who was the daughter
of the heir of Marius.

00:41:40.650 --> 00:41:43.260
And Caesar refused,
putting himself

00:41:43.260 --> 00:41:45.840
into a very dangerous situation.

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:51.150
He survived it, but this
prompted him to become really

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:56.100
a convinced populist
against this entrenched

00:41:56.100 --> 00:42:00.765
aristocracy in the Senate
that were the heirs of Sulla.

00:42:00.765 --> 00:42:04.320
And he was also a
very ambitious man.

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:06.160
He was a gambler.

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:09.300
He loved to play at high stakes.

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:12.060
And he was always
in debt and had

00:42:12.060 --> 00:42:15.870
to be bailed out, even before
he could leave for an earlier

00:42:15.870 --> 00:42:21.120
provincial command by the
richest man in Rome, Marcus

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:22.790
Crassus.

00:42:22.790 --> 00:42:27.900
And all that combined to
make a lot of enemies.

00:42:27.900 --> 00:42:31.620
The entrenched aristocracy
didn't like Caesar.

00:42:31.620 --> 00:42:33.960
And so they put all the
obstacles in his way

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:35.500
that they could.

00:42:35.500 --> 00:42:39.390
And he knew that he would
not secure an election

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:41.580
to the consulship,
the highest office,

00:42:41.580 --> 00:42:43.830
unless he had powerful allies.

00:42:43.830 --> 00:42:45.990
And so he formed
this Triple Alliance

00:42:45.990 --> 00:42:49.860
with Pompey, mentioned
before, and Crassus,

00:42:49.860 --> 00:42:54.600
who both had their reasons to
be at odds with the Senate.

00:42:54.600 --> 00:42:58.890
And they secured
Caesar's consulship.

00:42:58.890 --> 00:43:02.010
He did favors to them
and they did the favor

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:05.910
that they secured for him a
big provincial command in Gaul.

00:43:05.910 --> 00:43:08.400
Because in the
meantime, earlier Pompey

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.010
had done great
conquests in the east,

00:43:11.010 --> 00:43:16.650
fighting the famous
Mithridates and had

00:43:16.650 --> 00:43:20.430
added provinces and territories
to the Roman Empire.

00:43:20.430 --> 00:43:21.900
He had raised the bar.

00:43:21.900 --> 00:43:24.780
If one wanted to be
the greatest Roman,

00:43:24.780 --> 00:43:27.090
one had to be
better than Pompey.

00:43:27.090 --> 00:43:29.130
And Caesar was
extremely ambitious.

00:43:29.130 --> 00:43:32.790
And he, therefore,
secured these commands,

00:43:32.790 --> 00:43:35.340
and then hoped that there
would be an opportunity

00:43:35.340 --> 00:43:37.500
to create a war and start a war.

00:43:37.500 --> 00:43:42.000
And the Helvetians in the first
year gave him the opportunity.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:46.800
And out of this developed
this entire war, which he then

00:43:46.800 --> 00:43:50.470
described not only in his
reports to the Senate,

00:43:50.470 --> 00:43:53.850
but in these elaborated
commentaries,

00:43:53.850 --> 00:43:57.780
reports that we now
have and can read.

00:43:57.780 --> 00:44:00.540
And they gave us
so many insights

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:05.970
into how a leading
Roman of the time

00:44:05.970 --> 00:44:11.160
perceived his role, perceived
the role of the army, the role

00:44:11.160 --> 00:44:16.860
of a general, as Bob described
it, the role of a leader.

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:21.570
And I just put in a
few possible focuses

00:44:21.570 --> 00:44:25.290
one could talk about
in this context--

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:28.140
the perfect Roman,
the perfect general,

00:44:28.140 --> 00:44:31.260
which is very important
for Roman cultural history.

00:44:31.260 --> 00:44:34.380
He was an extremely
talented author as we

00:44:34.380 --> 00:44:36.240
shall see in a moment, I hope.

00:44:36.240 --> 00:44:39.420
And at the end,
I would just like

00:44:39.420 --> 00:44:42.540
to briefly talk about
what is the dark side

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:43.740
of this whole story.

00:44:43.740 --> 00:44:47.610
Namely, the brutality
of imperial conquest,

00:44:47.610 --> 00:44:51.300
the masses of losses
that it caused in Gaul.

00:44:51.300 --> 00:44:57.210
And balance this by looking at
Caesar as the clement victor

00:44:57.210 --> 00:45:00.720
because Caesar was very
innovative in this way as well.

00:45:00.720 --> 00:45:03.720
So I will see how far
I get with all this.

00:45:03.720 --> 00:45:08.400
This is Caesar, the
organizer and improviser.

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:10.530
Imagine for a
moment that this is

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:13.610
a war that is fought
in an unknown country.

00:45:13.610 --> 00:45:16.170
Caesar didn't know
where he was going.

00:45:16.170 --> 00:45:17.190
He didn't have maps.

00:45:17.190 --> 00:45:18.690
There were no maps.

00:45:18.690 --> 00:45:23.580
And there was no developed
good road network.

00:45:23.580 --> 00:45:28.500
So Caesar had to balance this
shortcoming by building up

00:45:28.500 --> 00:45:31.670
an extensive network of
intelligence, questioning

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:34.460
all kinds of people
about where he was going

00:45:34.460 --> 00:45:37.530
and where the goals were
that he was aiming at.

00:45:37.530 --> 00:45:40.580
A highly-developed
system of logistics,

00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:43.190
bringing the supplies
for an increasing number

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:45.830
of legions, tens of
thousands of soldiers

00:45:45.830 --> 00:45:51.560
who needed to be fed and
supported with boots, and so

00:45:51.560 --> 00:45:52.790
on.

00:45:52.790 --> 00:45:55.790
Reliance on the group
of favored allies

00:45:55.790 --> 00:45:58.670
who helped him with
difficulties that he

00:45:58.670 --> 00:46:03.110
might have in these
supplies, storage,

00:46:03.110 --> 00:46:05.300
increasing number
of hostages that

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:08.150
were given by the
defeated peoples that

00:46:08.150 --> 00:46:09.810
needed to be somewhere.

00:46:09.810 --> 00:46:13.940
Caesar couldn't take them
all along on his campaigns,

00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:16.610
so he relied on
some of these allies

00:46:16.610 --> 00:46:19.910
to take care of these hostages.

00:46:19.910 --> 00:46:23.750
He needed to be extremely
versatile in mastering

00:46:23.750 --> 00:46:28.420
the challenges of naval and
siege warfare, engineering.

00:46:28.420 --> 00:46:30.560
I'll show you an
example in a moment.

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:36.680
And in short, his
inventiveness was called for.

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:40.760
Circumspection, his ability
to think outside the box,

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:43.550
of finding solutions
that were unusual,

00:46:43.550 --> 00:46:47.240
understanding the conditions
under which his army fought,

00:46:47.240 --> 00:46:50.090
both from the enemy side
and from his own side.

00:46:50.090 --> 00:46:54.410
Caesar, for example, never
led his army into a fight

00:46:54.410 --> 00:46:57.530
before he knew that
they were rested enough

00:46:57.530 --> 00:47:01.460
and they had eaten before
they went into battle.

00:47:01.460 --> 00:47:03.480
One of his subcommanders
at some point

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:07.310
ignored these elementary
rules and promptly suffered

00:47:07.310 --> 00:47:08.195
very bad defeat.

00:47:10.820 --> 00:47:16.250
Using even deception
systematically and frequently,

00:47:16.250 --> 00:47:19.250
but always based on a
psychological assessment

00:47:19.250 --> 00:47:20.250
of the enemy.

00:47:20.250 --> 00:47:22.700
How far he could go,
how he could trick them.

00:47:22.700 --> 00:47:25.070
And he did that as
much as he could.

00:47:25.070 --> 00:47:30.140
But let me show you here another
aspect we tend to forget.

00:47:30.140 --> 00:47:33.170
Namely, that Caesar's
army was on its own.

00:47:33.170 --> 00:47:36.740
And he needed the specialists
in his army, the engineers,

00:47:36.740 --> 00:47:39.620
who would train the
soldiers to do the works.

00:47:39.620 --> 00:47:42.350
So they knew what
they had to do.

00:47:42.350 --> 00:47:44.690
The engineers provided
the blueprint.

00:47:44.690 --> 00:47:51.380
OK, this is going to be a
bridge with 20-feet-long timber

00:47:51.380 --> 00:47:52.790
crossing the Rhine.

00:47:52.790 --> 00:47:57.380
In 54, a bridge built
across the Rhine 400 meters

00:47:57.380 --> 00:48:02.990
wide and 12 feet deep
on average in 10 days

00:48:02.990 --> 00:48:05.970
once the lumber
started to come in.

00:48:05.970 --> 00:48:09.380
A major achievement-- and Caesar
tells about it very proudly

00:48:09.380 --> 00:48:13.070
because he was aware that he
had accomplished something

00:48:13.070 --> 00:48:14.840
very extraordinary here.

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:20.420
Or the ability to improvise
and surprise the enemy.

00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:25.250
His famous speed, the speed is
one of the most frequent words

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:28.430
that he uses, his celeritas.

00:48:28.430 --> 00:48:31.370
And there's an example
I give you here.

00:48:31.370 --> 00:48:36.230
His effort to get
back to his army

00:48:36.230 --> 00:48:40.880
when the big rebellion of
52 led by Vercingetorix

00:48:40.880 --> 00:48:42.230
had broken out.

00:48:42.230 --> 00:48:45.650
He came to the province
here in the south.

00:48:45.650 --> 00:48:47.490
Here's the province.

00:48:47.490 --> 00:48:52.810
And he had to get up here
where his legions were

00:48:52.810 --> 00:48:55.190
in winter quarters.

00:48:55.190 --> 00:48:59.590
And this was all enemy-infested,
rebellious territory.

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:02.050
And the enemy was convinced
that Caesar couldn't

00:49:02.050 --> 00:49:04.120
reach his legions
because they were

00:49:04.120 --> 00:49:06.800
in control of the territory.

00:49:06.800 --> 00:49:10.030
So what Caesar
did was he started

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:12.700
a diversionary attack
across a mountain

00:49:12.700 --> 00:49:15.580
range-- the Cevennes
mountains-- in winter.

00:49:15.580 --> 00:49:19.660
There were 10-feet-high
walls of snow and ice.

00:49:19.660 --> 00:49:24.310
And his army cut through
and made a path for him.

00:49:24.310 --> 00:49:28.850
He led parts of his army into
the territory of the Arverni,

00:49:28.850 --> 00:49:33.710
which was the tribe, the
nation of his enemy leader--

00:49:33.710 --> 00:49:34.750
general.

00:49:34.750 --> 00:49:37.930
And he started to
devastate the country.

00:49:37.930 --> 00:49:41.110
The Vercingetorix was
operating up here.

00:49:41.110 --> 00:49:46.330
He was called back by his people
to defend his own country.

00:49:46.330 --> 00:49:50.560
Caesar then himself went
back to the Rhone valley,

00:49:50.560 --> 00:49:54.250
joined a cavalry escort
that was well-rested here.

00:49:54.250 --> 00:49:55.990
And then in four
days and nights,

00:49:55.990 --> 00:50:00.700
dashed up to meet his
legions and reunite his army

00:50:00.700 --> 00:50:04.090
before the enemy even
knew what was going on.

00:50:04.090 --> 00:50:08.540
That is an example of his
inventiveness, of his speed,

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:14.860
of his ability to surprise
and reach success here.

00:50:14.860 --> 00:50:19.210
Another aspect I want to bring
out, which is his leadership.

00:50:19.210 --> 00:50:22.180
It's not the same
as his generalship.

00:50:22.180 --> 00:50:24.940
His ability to bond
with his soldiers,

00:50:24.940 --> 00:50:28.240
to create an army that
was in deep loyalty

00:50:28.240 --> 00:50:33.280
tied to him and of which he
could expect total effort,

00:50:33.280 --> 00:50:35.710
but he had to create this bond.

00:50:35.710 --> 00:50:39.760
And he was extremely
good in doing that.

00:50:39.760 --> 00:50:44.410
During a very difficult
siege at Avaricum, he--

00:50:44.410 --> 00:50:47.920
in winter, where the food
supply was interrupted

00:50:47.920 --> 00:50:51.370
because the enemy was using
a scorched earth strategy,

00:50:51.370 --> 00:50:55.150
Caesar offered to his
soldiers to give up.

00:50:55.150 --> 00:50:58.210
If this is too hard
for you, let's go.

00:50:58.210 --> 00:51:00.520
We can try something else.

00:51:00.520 --> 00:51:01.900
And the soldiers said, no.

00:51:01.900 --> 00:51:03.140
We never give up.

00:51:03.140 --> 00:51:04.180
We never gave up.

00:51:04.180 --> 00:51:07.870
We never betray you.

00:51:07.870 --> 00:51:11.050
So let's finish this up.

00:51:11.050 --> 00:51:13.900
But showing this
compassion, even

00:51:13.900 --> 00:51:18.070
sleeping out with his soldiers
on guard during the night,

00:51:18.070 --> 00:51:21.430
so that they knew he was
part of the enterprise

00:51:21.430 --> 00:51:25.450
and he was not somewhere
in a warm bunker,

00:51:25.450 --> 00:51:29.120
but he was right there where
the action was taking place.

00:51:29.120 --> 00:51:31.540
This is a hypothetical
reconstruction

00:51:31.540 --> 00:51:34.840
on the left of this siege.

00:51:34.840 --> 00:51:40.120
The siege works at Avaricum,
an 80-foot-high siege ramp,

00:51:40.120 --> 00:51:43.120
a tower, and covered galleries.

00:51:43.120 --> 00:51:46.580
And on the right,
I just showed you

00:51:46.580 --> 00:51:53.300
the Masada where the Roman siege
ramp is still visible here.

00:51:56.450 --> 00:52:00.590
So that is also a very steep
ramp on which a tower was then

00:52:00.590 --> 00:52:04.310
moved up so it could
shoot across the wall

00:52:04.310 --> 00:52:05.960
and defeat the enemies.

00:52:05.960 --> 00:52:09.230
You see the Roman
camps here and here.

00:52:09.230 --> 00:52:11.820
And there's one
down here as well.

00:52:11.820 --> 00:52:17.180
So this gives us an idea of
what was going on in Avaricum.

00:52:20.060 --> 00:52:23.660
Just very briefly other
aspects of leadership.

00:52:23.660 --> 00:52:24.680
Bob mentioned this.

00:52:24.680 --> 00:52:27.980
Exposing himself to
danger, taking the shield,

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:30.560
rushing to the front,
encouraging his soldiers.

00:52:30.560 --> 00:52:33.470
And through his
presence, giving courage

00:52:33.470 --> 00:52:37.790
to the soldiers who always in
the presence of the general

00:52:37.790 --> 00:52:42.890
tried to excel and show, and
of course, hope for rewards.

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:46.760
But this was very crucial
to stabilize the situation

00:52:46.760 --> 00:52:50.270
and actually, as I
say, steal victory out

00:52:50.270 --> 00:52:51.785
of the jaws of defeat.

00:52:54.620 --> 00:52:55.850
Then, other aspects.

00:52:55.850 --> 00:52:57.680
Caring for his soldiers' lives.

00:52:57.680 --> 00:53:00.890
Caesar often-- several
times at least--

00:53:00.890 --> 00:53:04.280
forfeited a certain
victory or an easy victory

00:53:04.280 --> 00:53:06.220
because he wanted
to avoid the losses

00:53:06.220 --> 00:53:08.840
this would cause
to his soldiers.

00:53:08.840 --> 00:53:12.230
He was very generous in
rewarding outstanding

00:53:12.230 --> 00:53:15.800
performances of
soldiers and officers.

00:53:15.800 --> 00:53:17.780
He shared the hardships.

00:53:17.780 --> 00:53:22.940
He was able to build up a
very deep sense of loyalty.

00:53:22.940 --> 00:53:26.000
He says at some point
during the civil war,

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:30.650
when two officers,
Gallic officers,

00:53:30.650 --> 00:53:33.800
deserted to the enemy, that
this was the first time

00:53:33.800 --> 00:53:35.450
ever that this has happened.

00:53:35.450 --> 00:53:38.030
While constantly
there was a flow of

00:53:38.030 --> 00:53:44.300
deserters from the enemy to
his camp in all his campaigns.

00:53:44.300 --> 00:53:49.400
And he gives us an example of
an officer who was captured

00:53:49.400 --> 00:53:54.560
and who was offered his
life and monetary rewards

00:53:54.560 --> 00:53:57.620
if he fought against
Caesar with his enemies.

00:53:57.620 --> 00:54:00.770
And he not only
refused to do that,

00:54:00.770 --> 00:54:04.310
but he offered the
commander of the enemy

00:54:04.310 --> 00:54:07.550
an opportunity to see
what the enemy was

00:54:07.550 --> 00:54:08.870
he was fighting against.

00:54:08.870 --> 00:54:13.940
He said, give me
10 men of my own

00:54:13.940 --> 00:54:17.750
and I will fight against the
whole company of your troops

00:54:17.750 --> 00:54:21.260
and you will see against
whom you are fighting.

00:54:21.260 --> 00:54:23.930
And then, of course, he
was immediately executed.

00:54:23.930 --> 00:54:27.650
But the story is told
by one of his officers

00:54:27.650 --> 00:54:30.720
as an example of this loyalty.

00:54:30.720 --> 00:54:34.160
And then, my favorite episode.

00:54:34.160 --> 00:54:36.180
Caesar was impatient.

00:54:36.180 --> 00:54:38.930
He departed for the
African war in 46,

00:54:38.930 --> 00:54:42.920
before his army had
completely assembled.

00:54:42.920 --> 00:54:47.270
And then there was a storm
and his whole flotilla

00:54:47.270 --> 00:54:48.980
was dispersed.

00:54:48.980 --> 00:54:52.400
He arrived with just a
couple of thousand soldiers

00:54:52.400 --> 00:54:54.650
and a few hundred cavalry.

00:54:54.650 --> 00:54:57.500
And for two days, the
others didn't show up.

00:54:57.500 --> 00:55:01.190
So he put soldiers on
ships in the harbor

00:55:01.190 --> 00:55:03.920
and waited during the night.

00:55:03.920 --> 00:55:06.470
He didn't tell his soldiers
what he had in mind

00:55:06.470 --> 00:55:08.360
because he knew that
there was communication

00:55:08.360 --> 00:55:10.040
across the fronts.

00:55:10.040 --> 00:55:15.680
And he didn't want his
plan to be betrayed.

00:55:15.680 --> 00:55:18.890
And then the soldiers
were very despondent.

00:55:18.890 --> 00:55:22.130
They knew they were a few,
they were inexperienced,

00:55:22.130 --> 00:55:24.720
they were new
recruits, and so on.

00:55:24.720 --> 00:55:29.420
And this is what
this author writes.

00:55:29.420 --> 00:55:33.200
This is, again, the officer
that writes this, not Caesar

00:55:33.200 --> 00:55:34.160
himself.

00:55:34.160 --> 00:55:36.020
"These soldiers
sitting on the ships

00:55:36.020 --> 00:55:38.090
could not find any
kind of comfort

00:55:38.090 --> 00:55:39.890
in their present circumstance.

00:55:39.890 --> 00:55:42.860
All they could do was look
to their general's face,

00:55:42.860 --> 00:55:47.030
which was full of heartiness
and unbelievably good spirits.

00:55:47.030 --> 00:55:49.250
His courage was like a standard.

00:55:49.250 --> 00:55:50.950
He carried in front.

00:55:50.950 --> 00:55:54.020
He carried straight up
high right in front of him.

00:55:54.020 --> 00:55:56.120
This calmed down the men.

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:58.520
And trusting his
expertise and planning,

00:55:58.520 --> 00:56:01.940
they all hoped that everything
would turn out well for them."

00:56:01.940 --> 00:56:05.630
Imagine-- this is the way
that they saw their general,

00:56:05.630 --> 00:56:06.380
these soldiers.

00:56:06.380 --> 00:56:11.100
That's part of the secret
of Caesar's success.

00:56:11.100 --> 00:56:12.870
I'm not going to
talk about this.

00:56:12.870 --> 00:56:16.940
Caesar was also a very talented
author, an intellectual

00:56:16.940 --> 00:56:18.530
of the highest rank.

00:56:18.530 --> 00:56:22.130
He could hold his own in
discussions with philosophers.

00:56:22.130 --> 00:56:26.720
And he was one of
the great orators.

00:56:26.720 --> 00:56:29.390
He only gave speeches at
the beginning of his career,

00:56:29.390 --> 00:56:31.310
but these made
such an impression

00:56:31.310 --> 00:56:35.690
that Cicero said he was ranking
among the highest, the best

00:56:35.690 --> 00:56:38.870
orators that Rome ever had.

00:56:38.870 --> 00:56:41.600
He was an expert in style.

00:56:41.600 --> 00:56:45.090
He wrote his historical
works, his commentaries,

00:56:45.090 --> 00:56:48.680
with the intention that
anybody could read them--

00:56:48.680 --> 00:56:50.990
uneducated/educated persons.

00:56:50.990 --> 00:56:56.120
And so he created a very simple,
straightforward, clear style

00:56:56.120 --> 00:56:59.630
that conveyed clearly
what he wanted to convey.

00:56:59.630 --> 00:57:04.710
And he wrote a work on good
style, good Latin style.

00:57:04.710 --> 00:57:06.620
And he dictated
this work while he

00:57:06.620 --> 00:57:10.280
was traveling on
horseback across the Alps

00:57:10.280 --> 00:57:12.380
to rejoin his army.

00:57:12.380 --> 00:57:14.360
Very unusual.

00:57:14.360 --> 00:57:20.630
And then, of course, he also
wrote these commentaries.

00:57:20.630 --> 00:57:23.150
And they were
praised very highly.

00:57:23.150 --> 00:57:26.390
I only gave you the
second quote by Hirtius,

00:57:26.390 --> 00:57:28.940
who wrote the eighth
book of the Gallic war.

00:57:28.940 --> 00:57:32.000
"The universal judgment
is that other writers,

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:37.790
despite their
painstaking efforts

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:39.890
have produced
nothing that is not

00:57:39.890 --> 00:57:43.850
outdone by the refined elegance
of Caesar's commentaries.

00:57:43.850 --> 00:57:46.850
They have been received
with unanimous approval.

00:57:46.850 --> 00:57:50.270
Yet we may feel greater
admiration than all others,

00:57:50.270 --> 00:57:54.210
for they know how well
and faultlessly he wrote,

00:57:54.210 --> 00:57:57.270
while we also know with
what ease and speed

00:57:57.270 --> 00:57:59.910
he completed the work."

00:57:59.910 --> 00:58:01.680
So this is Caesar,
the intellectual.

00:58:01.680 --> 00:58:04.290
Let me just for the
end, turn briefly

00:58:04.290 --> 00:58:06.030
to what I call "the dark side."

00:58:06.030 --> 00:58:10.140
Of course, this conquest of
Gaul caused enormous losses.

00:58:10.140 --> 00:58:14.040
Here you have the tally,
the casualty count.

00:58:14.040 --> 00:58:17.490
1 million Celts dead,
1 million enslaved.

00:58:17.490 --> 00:58:19.980
This is what ancient
authors tell us.

00:58:19.980 --> 00:58:23.400
Out of the population
of 8 to 12 million--

00:58:23.400 --> 00:58:27.150
reasonable estimates--
one fourth to one sixth

00:58:27.150 --> 00:58:31.110
of the total population
died in these conquests.

00:58:31.110 --> 00:58:35.220
In his triumph, in his great
victory celebration of 46,

00:58:35.220 --> 00:58:39.990
Caesar listed the total
number of casualties, enemy

00:58:39.990 --> 00:58:42.090
casualties, in his battles.

00:58:42.090 --> 00:58:46.680
Not just in Gaul, but
all over the place.

00:58:46.680 --> 00:58:49.260
1,192,000.

00:58:49.260 --> 00:58:51.060
These are staggering figures.

00:58:51.060 --> 00:58:54.545
And if you read
Caesar's story, when

00:58:54.545 --> 00:58:57.630
enemy swore an oath
of capitulation,

00:58:57.630 --> 00:59:00.990
and then broke the oath
and started to fight again,

00:59:00.990 --> 00:59:03.400
punishment was
absolutely brutal.

00:59:03.400 --> 00:59:08.380
Either execution or enslavement.

00:59:08.380 --> 00:59:11.130
This is from
Trajan's Column where

00:59:11.130 --> 00:59:14.045
you see a scene like that.

00:59:14.045 --> 00:59:18.420
The Gallic War is beautifully
illustrated by this spiral

00:59:18.420 --> 00:59:23.740
column in Rome, which is, of
course, almost 200 years later.

00:59:23.740 --> 00:59:26.400
But the army didn't change
much in the meantime.

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:28.360
And it, therefore,
gives us a good idea.

00:59:28.360 --> 00:59:31.980
And I just give you
two examples of where

00:59:31.980 --> 00:59:38.250
the label of genocide that has
sometimes been used for Caesar

00:59:38.250 --> 00:59:40.770
actually would apply.

00:59:40.770 --> 00:59:48.275
One is a campaign in 55,
where Caesar massacred

00:59:48.275 --> 00:59:52.380
two German nations that
had crossed over into Gaul,

00:59:52.380 --> 00:59:54.980
and that he distrusted deeply.

00:59:54.980 --> 00:59:56.460
He wanted them out.

00:59:56.460 --> 00:59:58.980
And since they didn't
react quickly enough,

00:59:58.980 --> 01:00:03.150
he just massacred
children, women, everybody.

01:00:03.150 --> 01:00:06.330
And he gives the
number as 430,000.

01:00:06.330 --> 01:00:08.220
Probably vastly exaggerated.

01:00:08.220 --> 01:00:12.450
But still, this was a
campaign of elimination.

01:00:12.450 --> 01:00:15.690
And that is very bad.

01:00:15.690 --> 01:00:19.370
And then, there was
one enemy leader,

01:00:19.370 --> 01:00:21.690
a leader of a Gallic nation.

01:00:21.690 --> 01:00:23.890
His name was Ambiorix.

01:00:23.890 --> 01:00:25.620
He had been a
friend of Caesar's.

01:00:25.620 --> 01:00:28.440
He had served in his army.

01:00:28.440 --> 01:00:31.980
And then he attacked
one of his winter camps

01:00:31.980 --> 01:00:35.820
and tricked the
Caesar subcommanders

01:00:35.820 --> 01:00:40.290
into leaving the camp, and
then ambushed and annihilated

01:00:40.290 --> 01:00:41.910
one and a half legions.

01:00:41.910 --> 01:00:47.360
And Caesar pursued this man
with deep hatred after that.

01:00:47.360 --> 01:00:50.380
And not only the man
himself, but his nation.

01:00:50.380 --> 01:00:53.760
And it was his goal to
eradicate this nation,

01:00:53.760 --> 01:00:57.690
so that if Ambiorix ever
came back to his nation,

01:00:57.690 --> 01:01:01.500
he would not find anybody
whom he could rely on.

01:01:01.500 --> 01:01:05.670
That was a campaign of
revenge and eradication.

01:01:05.670 --> 01:01:08.730
That is, again, quite radical.

01:01:08.730 --> 01:01:11.850
On the other hand, there
is a balance to this.

01:01:11.850 --> 01:01:16.230
Caesar is to my
knowledge, the first,

01:01:16.230 --> 01:01:19.440
perhaps the only
ancient general,

01:01:19.440 --> 01:01:23.220
who made clemency
his watch word, who

01:01:23.220 --> 01:01:31.350
declared it to be his goal
and his default action

01:01:31.350 --> 01:01:33.780
and did it whenever he could.

01:01:33.780 --> 01:01:38.280
If an enemy capitulated
before fighting broke out,

01:01:38.280 --> 01:01:41.040
they could expect
to suffer no harm.

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:44.730
And I give you two quotes
from the Gallic War.

01:01:44.730 --> 01:01:47.940
He said to a tribe
named the Atuatuci,

01:01:47.940 --> 01:01:50.070
"He would spare their nation--

01:01:50.070 --> 01:01:53.970
more because it was his habit
than because they deserved it--

01:01:53.970 --> 01:01:56.670
if they surrendered
before the battering ram

01:01:56.670 --> 01:01:58.470
touched their wall."

01:01:58.470 --> 01:02:03.000
And in the last year of the
war, in Uxellodunum, which was

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:06.270
mentioned by Bob, he punished--

01:02:06.270 --> 01:02:08.370
he had to set an
example because he

01:02:08.370 --> 01:02:11.760
wanted this constant
rebelling to stop.

01:02:11.760 --> 01:02:14.610
He knew his command
was coming to an end.

01:02:14.610 --> 01:02:18.330
He wanted to leave a
pacified and quiet country.

01:02:18.330 --> 01:02:21.000
And so he punished
when they capitulated.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:24.630
He punished the defenders,
the men who had been fighting,

01:02:24.630 --> 01:02:27.000
by cutting off their hands.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:30.840
Letting them live, but
cutting off their hands.

01:02:30.840 --> 01:02:35.010
And he writes, "Caesar was aware
that his merciful disposition

01:02:35.010 --> 01:02:37.920
was known to everyone,
and he did not

01:02:37.920 --> 01:02:41.670
need to be afraid that if he
acted more harshly than usual,

01:02:41.670 --> 01:02:46.350
it would be ascribed to
his cruel character."

01:02:46.350 --> 01:02:50.720
But then in the civil war,
both Pompey and Caesar

01:02:50.720 --> 01:02:54.140
were expected to
behave like Sulla had,

01:02:54.140 --> 01:02:59.030
with relentless persecution
of their opponents.

01:02:59.030 --> 01:03:01.220
And then after
his first victory,

01:03:01.220 --> 01:03:06.710
even a large number of elite
Romans fell into his hands.

01:03:06.710 --> 01:03:10.250
He let them sensationally
go unharmed.

01:03:10.250 --> 01:03:14.630
And that brought a big
turn in public opinion.

01:03:14.630 --> 01:03:19.040
And in a letter that was
disseminated throughout Italy--

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:20.930
and Cicero has a copy.

01:03:20.930 --> 01:03:23.900
And in his letters, we
can read that copy--

01:03:23.900 --> 01:03:26.505
he made this
programmatic statement

01:03:26.505 --> 01:03:28.730
to two of his supporters.

01:03:28.730 --> 01:03:31.850
"I'm glad that you approve of
what happened at Corfinium"--

01:03:31.850 --> 01:03:32.910
that's the place.

01:03:32.910 --> 01:03:34.910
"I had already
decided on a policy

01:03:34.910 --> 01:03:38.060
to demonstrate as much
leniency as possible.

01:03:38.060 --> 01:03:41.600
Let's try whether in
this way we can regain

01:03:41.600 --> 01:03:45.410
the goodwill of all people
and achieve lasting victory,

01:03:45.410 --> 01:03:48.410
because others have not
been able by cruelty

01:03:48.410 --> 01:03:51.200
to escape hatred and
to hold onto victory

01:03:51.200 --> 01:03:52.700
for any length of time--

01:03:52.700 --> 01:03:56.180
except only for Sulla whom
I not going to imitate.

01:03:56.180 --> 01:03:59.630
Let this be our new
way of conquering--

01:03:59.630 --> 01:04:03.800
to protect ourselves by
mercy and generosity."

01:04:03.800 --> 01:04:07.250
I find this one of the
very impressive statements

01:04:07.250 --> 01:04:10.760
in history.

01:04:10.760 --> 01:04:15.020
In an earlier episode
in the civil war,

01:04:15.020 --> 01:04:20.210
Caesar had trapped an enemy
army, immobilized them.

01:04:20.210 --> 01:04:24.920
And his army, his own army,
was sensing an easy victory

01:04:24.920 --> 01:04:27.830
and demanding the
command to attack.

01:04:27.830 --> 01:04:29.720
And Caesar refused.

01:04:29.720 --> 01:04:31.880
And he writes, "He
had come to hope

01:04:31.880 --> 01:04:35.000
that he could finish this
business without a battle

01:04:35.000 --> 01:04:38.600
and without exposing any
of his men to injury.

01:04:38.600 --> 01:04:42.290
Why, he thought, should he
risk losing some of his men,

01:04:42.290 --> 01:04:44.210
even in a successful battle?

01:04:44.210 --> 01:04:46.280
Why should he
accept that soldiers

01:04:46.280 --> 01:04:50.240
who had served him with supreme
loyalty would be wounded?

01:04:50.240 --> 01:04:53.510
He was also moved by pity
for his fellow citizens

01:04:53.510 --> 01:04:57.540
on the other side who, he
knew, would have to be killed.

01:04:57.540 --> 01:05:00.080
He preferred to achieve
his objective while they

01:05:00.080 --> 01:05:02.450
were safe and unharmed."

01:05:02.450 --> 01:05:05.300
And so he forced
them to capitulate

01:05:05.300 --> 01:05:07.050
by starving them out.

01:05:09.790 --> 01:05:13.960
So the idea, the
propagation of clemency

01:05:13.960 --> 01:05:17.680
as a general's and
ruler's cardinal virtue

01:05:17.680 --> 01:05:19.630
is Caesar's merit.

01:05:19.630 --> 01:05:22.750
And Augustus was the first,
who after the victory

01:05:22.750 --> 01:05:25.410
in the civil wars, was
given by the Senate

01:05:25.410 --> 01:05:31.650
a shield, a golden shield,
inscribed by the four--

01:05:31.650 --> 01:05:35.020
what became the four
cardinal virtues--

01:05:35.020 --> 01:05:38.620
virtue, clemency,
justice, and piety.

01:05:38.620 --> 01:05:40.300
And we have the inscription.

01:05:40.300 --> 01:05:42.310
We have copies of it.

01:05:42.310 --> 01:05:44.710
It's illustrated on coins.

01:05:44.710 --> 01:05:49.000
So Augustus was the first
who actually expressed

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:52.420
these cardinal virtues, but they
go back to Caesar's initiative.

01:05:52.420 --> 01:05:56.020
And I think that is worth
recording and mentioning

01:05:56.020 --> 01:06:00.200
because that also helps to
balance that dark picture which

01:06:00.200 --> 01:06:01.880
I drew earlier.

01:06:01.880 --> 01:06:03.390
Thank you very much.

01:06:03.390 --> 01:06:07.040
[APPLAUSE]

